Chapter 3: Java Methods

A method is a block of code which only runs when it is invoked. We can pass data (known as parameters) into a method. Methods are called to perform things, so we also called method as functions. It is much easier to define a method once and reuse it many times.

Java has some build-in methods like System.out.println(), However, we can make our own methods. Note, a method must be declared within a class.

aMethod () is the name. static means that this method belong to the Main class, and it is not a object of the Main class. void means that this method returns nothing.

Arithmetic Operators
Operator Name Description Example
 +  Additon  Adds together two values  a+b
 _  Substraction  Substract one value from another  a-b
 *  Multiplication  Multiple two values  a*b
 /  Division  Divides one value by another  a/b
 % Modulus  Returns the division remiander  a%b
 ++  Increment  Increase the value of a variable by 1  ++a
 --  Decrement  Decrease the value of a variable by 1  --a
Assignment Operators
Operator Example Same As
 =  a=5 a=5
 +=  a+=1 a=a+1
 -= a-=2 a=a-2
 *=  a*=3 x=x*3
/= a/=2 a=a/2

|=   a|=3  a=a|3
 ^=  a^=3  a=a^3
 >>=  a>>=3  a=a>>3
 <<=  a<<=3  a=a<<3
Comparision Operators
Operator Name Example
 == Equal to a==b
!= Not equal a!=b
> Greater than a>b
< Less than a<b
>= Greater than or equal to a>=b
 <=  Less than or equal to  a<=b
Logical Operators
Operator Name Description Example
&& Logical and Return true if both statement is true  a<8&&a<1
|| Logical or Return true if one of the statement is true  a<8||a<7
! Logical not Reverse the result, return false if the result is true  !(a<1&&A<4)
